{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"**Topology Summary**\n\nUse a 5 V single-supply transistor-level RC phase-shift oscillator with output node exactly `Vout`. The oscillator core should be an inverting, high-gain MOS analog amplifier biased around mid-supply, followed by a three-section RC phase-shift ladder that feeds back from `Vout` to the amplifier input. The RC ladder supplies approximately 180 degrees of phase shift at the oscillation frequency; the inverting gain stage supplies the remaining 180 degrees.\n\nTarget oscillation frequency should be in the approximate 5 kHz to 20 kHz range so `.tran 1u 5m` shows many visible cycles.\n\n**Device/Function List**\n\n- `VDD` supply source from `VDD` to ground, value 5 V.\n- Mid-supply reference generator producing `VREF` near 2.5 V, preferably a resistor divider from `VDD` to ground with optional bypass capacitor.\n- MOS transistor-level inverting gain stage:\n  - Output node must be `Vout`.\n  - Use real `NMOS`/`PMOS` devices only.\n  - Bulk terminals tied to each device source.\n  - Gain must comfortably exceed the passive RC ladder attenuation, typically requiring voltage gain greater than about 29 at startup.\n- Three RC ladder sections from `Vout` back to the amplifier input.\n- Bias resistors from RC/amplifier input nodes to `VREF` so no node floats in DC.\n- Startup assistance using `.ic` on one or more internal RC ladder/input nodes.\n\n**Bias/Reference Strategy**\n\nBias the amplifier input and output operating point around `VREF = 2.5 V`. The gain stage should settle near mid-rail in `.op`, with enough headroom for `Vout` to swing above and below 2.5 V without immediately clipping.\n\nIf using a single-ended common-source style gain block, bias the gate/input node near a valid operating point around `VREF`, and use active/current-source or resistive loading to obtain high gain.\n\nIf using a transistor-level differential gain block, keep explicit input nodes such as `Vinp` and `Vinn`. Bias one input at `VREF`, feed the final RC ladder node into the other input, and ensure polarity gives net loop inversion through the amplifier.\n\n**Signal Or Feedback Path**\n\nFeedback path should be explicit:\n\n`Vout -> RC section 1 -> RC section 2 -> RC section 3 -> amplifier input`\n\nUse three cascaded RC sections referenced to `VREF`, not floating capacitive-only nodes. Example node roles:\n\n- `Vout`: amplifier output and oscillator output.\n- `n1`: first RC ladder internal phase node.\n- `n2`: second RC ladder internal phase node.\n- `n3` or amplifier input node: final phase-shifted feedback node.\n- `VREF`: AC reference / virtual ground for ladder shunt elements and amplifier bias.\n\nThe final RC node drives the inverting amplifier input. Internal ladder nodes should show progressively shifted, lower-amplitude sine-like waveforms relative to `Vout`.\n\n**SPICE/Netlist Constraints**\n\n- Final filename: `p22.cir`.\n- Include node `Vout` exactly.\n- Include exactly:\n  - `.tran 1u 5m`\n- Use primitive SPICE devices: MOSFETs, resistors, capacitors, voltage sources.\n- Do not use behavioral sources, controlled sources, ideal op-amp macros, ideal limiters, or inverter-style rail-switching as the oscillator core.\n- Every internal RC node must have a DC path to `VREF` or ground.\n- Add `.ic` such as a small offset on the final RC node or amplifier input node to break perfect symmetry at startup.\n- Keep `Vout` unclamped unless normal transistor saturation naturally limits amplitude.\n\n**Failure Risks To Avoid**\n\n- Insufficient amplifier gain; the three-section RC ladder attenuates strongly, so loop gain must exceed unity at startup.\n- Floating RC ladder nodes caused by capacitors without DC bias paths.\n- Biasing the amplifier so `Vout` sits near a rail instead of near 2.5 V.\n- Accidentally building a hard CMOS inverter oscillator instead of an analog high-gain stage.\n- Using clamp diodes or ideal limiters on `Vout`, which can mask bad oscillator design.\n- Wrong feedback polarity: the RC ladder plus amplifier must produce total loop phase near 360 degrees.\n- R/C values that oscillate too slowly or too fast for `.tran 1u 5m`.\n- Perfectly symmetric initial conditions that prevent startup in transient simulation."}}
